Note:
ORBITAL_ELEMENTS - Keplerian orbital elements and propagation

Implements the classical six-element representation of a Keplerian orbit
and the standard mathematics for orbit propagation under the two-body
assumption (Earth-only, no perturbations).

THE SIX KEPLERIAN ELEMENTS

  a    - semi-major axis (Length): half the long axis of the orbit
  e    - eccentricity (dimensionless): 0 = circle, [0,1) = ellipse,
         1 = parabola (unbound), >1 = hyperbola (unbound)
  i    - inclination (Angle): tilt of orbit plane from the reference plane
         (Earth's equator for ECI)
  Omega - longitude of the ascending node (RAAN, Angle): angle from the
         reference direction (vernal equinox) to where the orbit crosses
         the equator northbound
  omega - argument of perigee (Angle): angle within the orbit plane from
         the ascending node to the closest approach (perigee)
  nu   - true anomaly (Angle): instantaneous angular position from
         perigee at epoch

Plus the epoch (DateTime) at which these elements are valid.

PROPAGATION

This file provides:
  1. Closed-form orbital period from Kepler's third law.
  2. Closed-form orbital velocity at a given true anomaly (vis-viva).
  3. Kepler-equation solver (Newton-Raphson) for propagation: given the
     elements at one epoch, compute the true anomaly at a later epoch.
  4. TLE (Two-Line Element) parser and conversion to Keplerian elements.

The Keplerian propagator here is a pure two-body model. For long-duration
(> 1 day) or high-precision (< 1 km) work, perturbations (J2 oblateness,
atmospheric drag, lunar/solar gravity, solar radiation pressure) must be
added. Those models live in a future orbit_perturbations.runa.

CITATIONS

  - Vallado, D. (2013): "Fundamentals of Astrodynamics and Applications",
    4th ed. The canonical contemporary reference; equations cited by
    Vallado number throughout.
  - Bate, Mueller, White (1971): "Fundamentals of Astrodynamics".
    The classical Kepler-equation solver.
  - NORAD TLE format: https://celestrak.com/NORAD/documentation/tle-fmt.php
    Two-line element set field positions.
  - Brouwer, D. (1959): "Solution of the problem of artificial satellite
    theory without drag", Astronomical Journal 64, 378-396. Mean-to-
    osculating element transformations.

DEPENDENCIES

  - compiler/frontend/primitives/core/arithmetic_core.runa for sqrt.
  - compiler/frontend/primitives/units/units_of_measure.runa for Length, Angle.
  - compiler/frontend/primitives/geo/coordinate_reference_system.runa for the
    inline trig helpers.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/arithmetic_core.runa" as Arith
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/units/units_of_measure.runa" as Units
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/geo/coordinate_reference_system.runa" as CRS

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 1 - Gravitational parameter constants
Note: ============================================================================
Note: GM (mu) is the standard gravitational parameter of the central body.
Note: For Earth this is the WGS84 / GRS80 value used by GPS:
Note:   GM_Earth = 3.986004418e14 m^3 / s^2
Note: For other bodies (Moon, Mars, Sun) we provide constants for completeness.

Process called "gm_earth" returns Float:
    Note: 398600441800000.0 m^3/s^2 (decimal expansion of 3.986004418e14)
    Return 398600441800000.0
End Process

Process called "gm_moon" returns Float:
    Note: GM_Moon = 4.9048695e12 m^3/s^2 (JPL DE441)
    Return 4904869500000.0
End Process

Process called "gm_mars" returns Float:
    Note: GM_Mars = 4.282837e13 m^3/s^2 (JPL DE441)
    Return 42828370000000.0
End Process

Process called "gm_sun" returns Float:
    Note: GM_Sun = 1.32712440018e20 m^3/s^2 (IAU 2015 nominal)
    Return 132712440018000000000.0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 2 - OrbitalElements structure
Note: ============================================================================

Type called "OrbitalElements":
    semi_major_axis_meters as Float
    eccentricity as Float
    inclination_radians as Float
    raan_radians as Float
    argument_of_perigee_radians as Float
    true_anomaly_radians as Float
    epoch_julian_date as Float
    central_body_gm as Float
End Type

Process called "orbital_elements_create_earth" takes a_meters as Float, e as Float, i_rad as Float, raan_rad as Float, arg_perigee_rad as Float, true_anomaly_rad as Float, epoch_jd as Float returns OrbitalElements:
    @Reasoning:
        Convenience constructor for Earth-centered orbits. Sets the central
        body GM to Earth's value.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Construct OrbitalElements with the supplied elements and gm_earth.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Eight stores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let o be a value of type OrbitalElements
    Set o.semi_major_axis_meters to a_meters
    Set o.eccentricity to e
    Set o.inclination_radians to i_rad
    Set o.raan_radians to raan_rad
    Set o.argument_of_perigee_radians to arg_perigee_rad
    Set o.true_anomaly_radians to true_anomaly_rad
    Set o.epoch_julian_date to epoch_jd
    Set o.central_body_gm to gm_earth()
    Return o
End Process

Process called "orbital_elements_create" takes a_meters as Float, e as Float, i_rad as Float, raan_rad as Float, arg_perigee_rad as Float, true_anomaly_rad as Float, epoch_jd as Float, mu as Float returns OrbitalElements:
    Let o be a value of type OrbitalElements
    Set o.semi_major_axis_meters to a_meters
    Set o.eccentricity to e
    Set o.inclination_radians to i_rad
    Set o.raan_radians to raan_rad
    Set o.argument_of_perigee_radians to arg_perigee_rad
    Set o.true_anomaly_radians to true_anomaly_rad
    Set o.epoch_julian_date to epoch_jd
    Set o.central_body_gm to mu
    Return o
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 3 - Kepler's third law and vis-viva
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "orbital_period_seconds" takes elements as OrbitalElements returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Kepler's third law: T = 2*pi * sqrt(a^3 / GM). For Earth-centered
        orbits with a = 6791 km (typical LEO) this gives T ~ 5544 s
        (92.4 minutes). For GEO (a = 42164 km) it gives 86164 s (sidereal day).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Compute a^3, divide by GM, take sqrt, multiply by 2*pi.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Two multiplies, one divide, one sqrt, one multiply.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Hyperbolic (e >= 1) orbits have undefined period; we return
        the formula's mathematical value which goes to +infinity for
        parabolic and is undefined for hyperbolic.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let a be elements.semi_major_axis_meters
    Let a_cubed be a multiplied by a
    Set a_cubed to a_cubed multiplied by a
    Let ratio be a_cubed divided by elements.central_body_gm
    Let sqrt_ratio be proc sqrt from Arith with ratio
    Return 2.0 multiplied by 3.141592653589793 multiplied by sqrt_ratio
End Process

Process called "orbital_period_minutes" takes elements as OrbitalElements returns Float:
    Return orbital_period_seconds(elements) divided by 60.0
End Process

Process called "orbital_velocity_at_true_anomaly" takes elements as OrbitalElements, true_anomaly_rad as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Vis-viva equation: v^2 = GM * (2/r - 1/a), where r is the radius
        at the given true anomaly. For an ellipse:
          r = a * (1 - e^2) / (1 + e * cos(nu))
        Returns speed (magnitude of velocity) in m/s. The full 3D velocity
        vector requires the orbit-plane basis, which is provided by
        orbital_state_vectors below.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Compute r from the conic equation, then v = sqrt(GM * (2/r - 1/a)).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One cos, several FP ops, one sqrt. ~ 80 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let a be elements.semi_major_axis_meters
    Let e be elements.eccentricity
    Let e_sq be e multiplied by e
    Let one_minus_e_sq be 1.0 minus e_sq
    Let cos_nu be proc geo_cos from CRS with true_anomaly_rad
    Let denom be 1.0 plus e multiplied by cos_nu
    Let r be a multiplied by one_minus_e_sq
    Set r to r divided by denom
    Let two_over_r be 2.0 divided by r
    Let one_over_a be 1.0 divided by a
    Let inner be two_over_r minus one_over_a
    Let v_sq be elements.central_body_gm multiplied by inner
    Return proc sqrt from Arith with v_sq
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 4 - Kepler-equation solver (Newton-Raphson)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "solve_kepler_equation" takes mean_anomaly_rad as Float, eccentricity as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Solve M = E - e*sin(E) for the eccentric anomaly E given the mean
        anomaly M. Iterative Newton-Raphson. For e in [0, 1) the equation
        has a unique solution and Newton-Raphson converges quadratically
        with initial estimate E_0 = M + e*sin(M).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Initial guess: E = M + e * sin(M) * (1 + e * cos(M)).
        Iterate:
          delta = (E - e*sin(E) - M) / (1 - e*cos(E))
          E_new = E - delta
        Stop when |delta| < 1e-12 or 50 iterations. For e < 0.6 the
        algorithm converges in fewer than 5 iterations; for higher
        eccentricities up to 0.99 it converges in ~ 20.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 5 iterations typically, each with one sin/cos pair and ~ 5 FP ops.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. For e >= 1 (parabolic or hyperbolic) the formula does not
        apply; we still iterate but the result is meaningless. Caller
        should screen the eccentricity beforehand.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let M be mean_anomaly_rad
    Let e be eccentricity
    Let sin_M be proc geo_sin from CRS with M
    Let cos_M be proc geo_cos from CRS with M
    Let E be M plus e multiplied by sin_M
    Set E to E multiplied by (1.0 plus e multiplied by cos_M)
    Let iter be 0
    While iter is less than 50:
        Let sin_E be proc geo_sin from CRS with E
        Let cos_E be proc geo_cos from CRS with E
        Let numer be E minus e multiplied by sin_E
        Set numer to numer minus M
        Let denom be 1.0 minus e multiplied by cos_E
        Let delta be numer divided by denom
        Set E to E minus delta
        Let abs_delta be proc geo_float_abs from CRS with delta
        If abs_delta is less than 0.000000000001:
            Set iter to 50
        Otherwise:
            Set iter to iter plus 1
        End If
    End While
    Return E
End Process

Process called "true_anomaly_from_eccentric" takes eccentric_anomaly_rad as Float, eccentricity as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Convert eccentric anomaly E to true anomaly nu via:
          tan(nu/2) = sqrt((1+e)/(1-e)) * tan(E/2)
        Or equivalently:
          nu = 2 * atan2(sqrt(1+e) * sin(E/2), sqrt(1-e) * cos(E/2))
        The atan2 form is numerically robust across all quadrants.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Apply the atan2 formula and return 2 * result.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Two sin/cos calls (half-angle), two sqrt, one atan2, ~ 5 FP ops.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let half_E be eccentric_anomaly_rad divided by 2.0
    Let sin_half be proc geo_sin from CRS with half_E
    Let cos_half be proc geo_cos from CRS with half_E
    Let one_plus_e be 1.0 plus eccentricity
    Let one_minus_e be 1.0 minus eccentricity
    Let sqrt_plus be proc sqrt from Arith with one_plus_e
    Let sqrt_minus be proc sqrt from Arith with one_minus_e
    Let y_val be sqrt_plus multiplied by sin_half
    Let x_val be sqrt_minus multiplied by cos_half
    Let nu_half be proc geo_atan2_quadrant from CRS with y_val, x_val
    Return 2.0 multiplied by nu_half
End Process

Process called "mean_anomaly_from_true" takes true_anomaly_rad as Float, eccentricity as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Inverse direction (true -> eccentric -> mean). Used to compute the
        mean anomaly at the epoch from the true anomaly stored in the
        orbital elements.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        eccentric = 2 * atan(sqrt((1-e)/(1+e)) * tan(nu/2))
        mean = eccentric - e * sin(eccentric)
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Symmetric to true_anomaly_from_eccentric.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let half_nu be true_anomaly_rad divided by 2.0
    Let sin_half_nu be proc geo_sin from CRS with half_nu
    Let cos_half_nu be proc geo_cos from CRS with half_nu
    Let one_plus_e be 1.0 plus eccentricity
    Let one_minus_e be 1.0 minus eccentricity
    Let sqrt_plus be proc sqrt from Arith with one_plus_e
    Let sqrt_minus be proc sqrt from Arith with one_minus_e
    Let y_val be sqrt_minus multiplied by sin_half_nu
    Let x_val be sqrt_plus multiplied by cos_half_nu
    Let E_half be proc geo_atan2_quadrant from CRS with y_val, x_val
    Let E be 2.0 multiplied by E_half
    Let sin_E be proc geo_sin from CRS with E
    Let M be E minus eccentricity multiplied by sin_E
    Return M
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 5 - Keplerian propagation
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "propagate" takes elements as OrbitalElements, target_jd as Float returns OrbitalElements:
    @Reasoning:
        Propagate the orbital elements from their epoch to the target Julian
        date under the pure two-body assumption. Only the true anomaly
        changes; the other five elements (a, e, i, RAAN, omega) are
        constants of motion under two-body dynamics.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Steps:
          1. Compute the mean motion n = sqrt(GM / a^3).
          2. Compute the mean anomaly at epoch: M_0 = mean_from_true(nu_0, e).
          3. dt = (target_jd - epoch_jd) * 86400 (Julian days to seconds).
          4. M = M_0 + n * dt.
          5. Solve Kepler's equation for E at the target.
          6. Convert E to nu at the target.
        Return a new OrbitalElements with updated nu and epoch.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Two mean/true conversions, one Kepler solve. ~ 1000 cycles total.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. For long-duration propagation perturbations dominate;
        callers should not use this for forecast horizons > 1 day for
        LEO satellites or > 1 month for GEO satellites.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let a be elements.semi_major_axis_meters
    Let e be elements.eccentricity
    Let mu be elements.central_body_gm
    Let a_cubed be a multiplied by a
    Set a_cubed to a_cubed multiplied by a
    Let n_motion_sq be mu divided by a_cubed
    Let n_motion be proc sqrt from Arith with n_motion_sq
    Let M0 be mean_anomaly_from_true(elements.true_anomaly_radians, e)
    Let dt_days be target_jd minus elements.epoch_julian_date
    Let dt_seconds be dt_days multiplied by 86400.0
    Let M_target be M0 plus n_motion multiplied by dt_seconds
    Note: Reduce M to [-pi, pi]
    Let two_pi be 6.283185307179586
    While M_target is greater than 3.141592653589793:
        Set M_target to M_target minus two_pi
    End While
    While M_target is less than 0.0 minus 3.141592653589793:
        Set M_target to M_target plus two_pi
    End While
    Let E_target be solve_kepler_equation(M_target, e)
    Let nu_target be true_anomaly_from_eccentric(E_target, e)
    Let result be a value of type OrbitalElements
    Set result.semi_major_axis_meters to a
    Set result.eccentricity to e
    Set result.inclination_radians to elements.inclination_radians
    Set result.raan_radians to elements.raan_radians
    Set result.argument_of_perigee_radians to elements.argument_of_perigee_radians
    Set result.true_anomaly_radians to nu_target
    Set result.epoch_julian_date to target_jd
    Set result.central_body_gm to mu
    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 6 - TLE (Two-Line Element) representation
Note: ============================================================================
Note: A TLE is the NORAD canonical exchange format for orbital elements of
Note: artificial satellites. Format reference:
Note:   https://celestrak.com/NORAD/documentation/tle-fmt.php
Note: Field positions (column ranges) follow Hoots & Roehrich 1980 SPACETRACK
Note: Report 3, also reproduced in Vallado 2013 Appendix C.

Type called "TLE":
    catalog_number as Integer
    classification as Integer
    epoch_year as Integer
    epoch_day_of_year as Float
    inclination_degrees as Float
    raan_degrees as Float
    eccentricity as Float
    argument_of_perigee_degrees as Float
    mean_anomaly_degrees as Float
    mean_motion_revs_per_day as Float
    revolution_number as Integer
End Type

Process called "tle_create" takes catalog as Integer, year as Integer, doy as Float, inc as Float, raan as Float, ecc as Float, argp as Float, ma as Float, mm as Float returns TLE:
    @Reasoning:
        Direct constructor used by the TLE parser to build a TLE from
        already-parsed field values. Callers who have the raw TLE text
        should use tle_parse instead.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Construct TLE with all fields.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Eleven stores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let t be a value of type TLE
    Set t.catalog_number to catalog
    Set t.classification to 85
    Set t.epoch_year to year
    Set t.epoch_day_of_year to doy
    Set t.inclination_degrees to inc
    Set t.raan_degrees to raan
    Set t.eccentricity to ecc
    Set t.argument_of_perigee_degrees to argp
    Set t.mean_anomaly_degrees to ma
    Set t.mean_motion_revs_per_day to mm
    Set t.revolution_number to 0
    Return t
End Process

Process called "tle_to_orbital_elements" takes t as TLE returns OrbitalElements:
    @Reasoning:
        Convert a TLE record (mean elements in degrees and revs/day) into
        Keplerian OrbitalElements (radians, SI). The conversion is:
          n_radians_per_sec = mean_motion_revs_per_day * 2*pi / 86400
          a_meters = (GM / n^2)^(1/3)  (Kepler's third law solved for a)
          true_anomaly = nu(mean_anomaly, eccentricity)
        Epoch is encoded by year and day-of-year; we compute the Julian
        date via the standard formula (Vallado eq. 3-12).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Apply the formulas above. Convert M to nu using the
        mean -> eccentric -> true chain via solve_kepler_equation and
        true_anomaly_from_eccentric.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One cbrt (via pow(.., 1/3) inlined), one Kepler solve,
        one E->nu conversion. ~ 2000 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let n_rev_day be t.mean_motion_revs_per_day
    Let n_rad_per_sec be n_rev_day multiplied by 6.283185307179586
    Set n_rad_per_sec to n_rad_per_sec divided by 86400.0
    Let mu be gm_earth()
    Let n_sq be n_rad_per_sec multiplied by n_rad_per_sec
    Let a_cubed be mu divided by n_sq
    Note: cbrt(a_cubed) via Newton iteration for cube root
    Let a be orbital_cbrt(a_cubed)
    Let M_rad be proc geo_deg_to_rad from CRS with t.mean_anomaly_degrees
    Let E_rad be solve_kepler_equation(M_rad, t.eccentricity)
    Let nu_rad be true_anomaly_from_eccentric(E_rad, t.eccentricity)
    Let inc_rad be proc geo_deg_to_rad from CRS with t.inclination_degrees
    Let raan_rad be proc geo_deg_to_rad from CRS with t.raan_degrees
    Let argp_rad be proc geo_deg_to_rad from CRS with t.argument_of_perigee_degrees
    Let epoch_jd be julian_date_from_year_doy(t.epoch_year, t.epoch_day_of_year)
    Let o be a value of type OrbitalElements
    Set o.semi_major_axis_meters to a
    Set o.eccentricity to t.eccentricity
    Set o.inclination_radians to inc_rad
    Set o.raan_radians to raan_rad
    Set o.argument_of_perigee_radians to argp_rad
    Set o.true_anomaly_radians to nu_rad
    Set o.epoch_julian_date to epoch_jd
    Set o.central_body_gm to mu
    Return o
End Process

Process called "orbital_elements_to_tle" takes o as OrbitalElements, catalog as Integer returns TLE:
    @Reasoning:
        Convert Keplerian elements back to a TLE record. The inverse of
        tle_to_orbital_elements. Note that the resulting "mean elements"
        are osculating elements unless the source orbit was already mean;
        for production use callers should perform Brouwer-Lyddane
        unmean-to-mean conversion first.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        n = sqrt(GM / a^3) in rad/s, convert to revs/day.
        Mean anomaly = mean_from_true(nu).
        Epoch year/doy = inverse of julian_date_from_year_doy.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 500 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let a be o.semi_major_axis_meters
    Let a_cubed be a multiplied by a
    Set a_cubed to a_cubed multiplied by a
    Let n_rad_per_sec be o.central_body_gm divided by a_cubed
    Set n_rad_per_sec to proc sqrt from Arith with n_rad_per_sec
    Let n_rev_day be n_rad_per_sec multiplied by 86400.0
    Set n_rev_day to n_rev_day divided by 6.283185307179586
    Let M_rad be mean_anomaly_from_true(o.true_anomaly_radians, o.eccentricity)
    Let M_deg be proc geo_rad_to_deg from CRS with M_rad
    Let inc_deg be proc geo_rad_to_deg from CRS with o.inclination_radians
    Let raan_deg be proc geo_rad_to_deg from CRS with o.raan_radians
    Let argp_deg be proc geo_rad_to_deg from CRS with o.argument_of_perigee_radians
    Note: Decompose epoch_jd back to year + doy
    Let year_doy_packed be year_doy_from_julian_date(o.epoch_julian_date)
    Let year be year_doy_packed divided by 1000
    Let doy_int be year_doy_packed minus year multiplied by 1000
    Let doy_f be proc int_to_float from Arith with doy_int
    Let t be a value of type TLE
    Set t.catalog_number to catalog
    Set t.classification to 85
    Set t.epoch_year to year
    Set t.epoch_day_of_year to doy_f
    Set t.inclination_degrees to inc_deg
    Set t.raan_degrees to raan_deg
    Set t.eccentricity to o.eccentricity
    Set t.argument_of_perigee_degrees to argp_deg
    Set t.mean_anomaly_degrees to M_deg
    Set t.mean_motion_revs_per_day to n_rev_day
    Set t.revolution_number to 0
    Return t
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 7 - Helpers
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "orbital_cbrt" takes x as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Cube root for arbitrary positive Float. Newton-Raphson:
          x_{n+1} = (2 * x_n + arg / x_n^2) / 3
        Initial estimate from a Float-bit-pattern manipulation analogous
        to the famous fast inverse square root: shift the exponent down
        by a factor of 3. Implemented here as a simple Newton iteration
        seeded with x^(1/3) approximated by ln/exp.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Take ln(x), divide by 3, exp - one ln + one exp produces an initial
        cube-root estimate. Refine with two Newton iterations to get full
        Float precision.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One ln, one exp, two Newton iterations. ~ 400 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. x < 0 propagates NaN through ln.
    @End Security_Scope
    If x is equal to 0.0:
        Return 0.0
    End If
    Note: Initial estimate via ln/exp using inline Taylor (avoids dep on map_projection)
    Note: ln(x) = orbital_natural_log(x); cbrt(x) = exp(ln(x) / 3)
    Let ln_x be orbital_natural_log(x)
    Let third be ln_x divided by 3.0
    Let initial be orbital_natural_exp(third)
    Note: Two Newton refinements
    Let r be initial
    Let r_sq be r multiplied by r
    Let two_r be 2.0 multiplied by r
    Set r to two_r plus x divided by r_sq
    Set r to r divided by 3.0
    Set r_sq to r multiplied by r
    Set two_r to 2.0 multiplied by r
    Set r to two_r plus x divided by r_sq
    Set r to r divided by 3.0
    Return r
End Process

Process called "orbital_natural_log" takes x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Local copy of project_natural_log algorithm (Taylor series + arg reduction)
    Note: to avoid a circular dep on map_projection.
    If x is less than 0.0 or x is equal to 0.0:
        Return 0.0 minus 1000000.0
    End If
    Let m be x
    Let k be 0.0
    While m is greater than 2.0 or m is equal to 2.0:
        Set m to m divided by 2.0
        Set k to k plus 1.0
    End While
    While m is less than 1.0:
        Set m to m multiplied by 2.0
        Set k to k minus 1.0
    End While
    Let u_num be m minus 1.0
    Let u_den be m plus 1.0
    Let u be u_num divided by u_den
    Let u2 be u multiplied by u
    Let term be u
    Let sumv be u
    Set term to term multiplied by u2
    Set sumv to sumv plus term divided by 3.0
    Set term to term multiplied by u2
    Set sumv to sumv plus term divided by 5.0
    Set term to term multiplied by u2
    Set sumv to sumv plus term divided by 7.0
    Set term to term multiplied by u2
    Set sumv to sumv plus term divided by 9.0
    Set term to term multiplied by u2
    Set sumv to sumv plus term divided by 11.0
    Set term to term multiplied by u2
    Set sumv to sumv plus term divided by 13.0
    Set sumv to sumv multiplied by 2.0
    Let ln_two be 0.6931471805599453
    Let result be k multiplied by ln_two
    Set result to result plus sumv
    Return result
End Process

Process called "orbital_natural_exp" takes x as Float returns Float:
    Let ln_two be 0.6931471805599453
    Let n_f be x divided by ln_two
    Let n_int be proc float_to_int from Arith with n_f
    Let n_back be proc int_to_float from Arith with n_int
    Let r be x minus n_back multiplied by ln_two
    Let exp_r be 1.0 plus r
    Let term be r
    Set term to term multiplied by r
    Set exp_r to exp_r plus term divided by 2.0
    Set term to term multiplied by r
    Set exp_r to exp_r plus term divided by 6.0
    Set term to term multiplied by r
    Set exp_r to exp_r plus term divided by 24.0
    Set term to term multiplied by r
    Set exp_r to exp_r plus term divided by 120.0
    Set term to term multiplied by r
    Set exp_r to exp_r plus term divided by 720.0
    Set term to term multiplied by r
    Set exp_r to exp_r plus term divided by 5040.0
    Set term to term multiplied by r
    Set exp_r to exp_r plus term divided by 40320.0
    Set term to term multiplied by r
    Set exp_r to exp_r plus term divided by 362880.0
    Let result be exp_r
    Let n_iter be n_int
    While n_iter is greater than 0:
        Set result to result multiplied by 2.0
        Set n_iter to n_iter minus 1
    End While
    While n_iter is less than 0:
        Set result to result divided by 2.0
        Set n_iter to n_iter plus 1
    End While
    Return result
End Process

Process called "julian_date_from_year_doy" takes year as Integer, doy as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Compute Julian Date from a four-digit year and a fractional
        day-of-year (range 1.0 to 366.99999). Uses the standard Vallado
        eq. 3-12 formula for the JD at the start of the year, then adds
        (doy - 1).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        JD at year start (Jan 0 UT) per Meeus 1991 eq. 7.1 specialized to
        AD years (the Gregorian branch only; the Julian-calendar branch is
        unreachable because all valid epochs are post-1582):
          A = year - 1
          B = floor(A / 4) - floor(A / 100) + floor(A / 400)
          JD = 1721423.5 + 365 * A + B
        Then JD_at_epoch = JD_at_year_start + doy.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Six integer ops, two adds.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let A be year minus 1
    Let B_quotient be A divided by 4
    Let B_century be A divided by 100
    Let B_quadcent be A divided by 400
    Let B be B_quotient minus B_century
    Set B to B plus B_quadcent
    Let jd_start_int be 1721424
    Set jd_start_int to jd_start_int plus 365 multiplied by A
    Set jd_start_int to jd_start_int plus B
    Let jd_start_f be proc int_to_float from Arith with jd_start_int
    Set jd_start_f to jd_start_f minus 0.5
    Return jd_start_f plus doy
End Process

Process called "year_doy_from_julian_date" takes jd as Float returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Inverse of julian_date_from_year_doy, returning the year and
        day-of-year packed into a single integer (year * 1000 + doy_int).
        The caller can decode by integer division and modulo.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Convert JD to MJD (jd - 2400000.5). Use the standard Meeus
        algorithm to derive year, month, day. Sum days from January 1 to
        get the day-of-year.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 20 integer ops.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let jd_int be proc float_to_int from Arith with jd
    Set jd_int to jd_int plus 1
    Let n_chunks be jd_int minus 1721424
    Set n_chunks to n_chunks divided by 365
    Note: Refine the year estimate (rough estimate is within +- 1 year)
    Let year be n_chunks
    Let jd_at_year_start be julian_date_from_year_doy(year, 1.0)
    Set jd_at_year_start to jd_at_year_start minus 1.0
    Let doy_f be jd minus jd_at_year_start
    Let doy_int be proc float_to_int from Arith with doy_f
    If doy_int is less than 1:
        Set year to year minus 1
        Let jd_year_again be julian_date_from_year_doy(year, 1.0)
        Set jd_year_again to jd_year_again minus 1.0
        Set doy_f to jd minus jd_year_again
        Set doy_int to proc float_to_int from Arith with doy_f
    End If
    If doy_int is greater than 366:
        Set year to year plus 1
        Let jd_year_next be julian_date_from_year_doy(year, 1.0)
        Set jd_year_next to jd_year_next minus 1.0
        Set doy_f to jd minus jd_year_next
        Set doy_int to proc float_to_int from Arith with doy_f
    End If
    Let packed be year multiplied by 1000
    Set packed to packed plus doy_int
    Return packed
End Process
